ong-standing dichotomies between East and West and embracing a capacious understanding of translatio as geographic movement, linquistic transformation, and cultural grafting, the collection gives pride of place to convergence, approximation, and hybridity, thus underscoring the radical mobility of early modern culture. In so doing, England's Asian Renaissance also moves away from entrenched narratives of Western cultural sovereignty to think anew England's debts to Asia. Published by the University of Delaware Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEast and West in literature. 0aEnglish literaturexAsian influences. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 70(DE-588)4014777-00(DE-627)1063387490(DE-576)208909400aEnglisch2gnd 70(DE-588)4035964-50(DE-627)1062450150(DE-576)209015608aLiteratur2gnd 70(DE-588)4266459-70(DE-627)1045619710(DE-576)210637358aAsiengMotiv2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAsian, England, english, english language, Eastern themes, Asian Knowledge, Asia, early modern culture, East, West, customs, cross-cultural fertilization, Asian culture, English cultural, political sovereignty, translation.1 aArvas, Abdulhamit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArvas, Abdulhamit.1 aBarbour, Richmond, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbour, Richmond.1 aBuckley, Thea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuckley, Thea.1 aFang Ng, Su, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeather, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeather, Jennifer.1 aMehdizadeh, Nedda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1